{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502500"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1867"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583030"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:04:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:04:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1867"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1867"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.01,0.06,0.52,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1867"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90506"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1867"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1867"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74746"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"539"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31042"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90506"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 42-year-old man presents to his general practitioner after experiencing an episode of upper abdominal pain the previous day. The pain came on rapidly over ten minutes, was constant in nature and lasted about one hour before it fully resolved. The pain was worse in his right upper quadrant and radiated around to his back. He had never had these symptoms before, is normally in good health and his medical history is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 124/80 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2C. His abdomen is soft, with no areas of tenderness. Examination of his chest is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum lipase","Plain abdominal X-ray","ECG","Upper abdominal ultrasound","CT abdomen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFrom the information provided in the stem, the most likely diagnosis is biliary colic. This type of gallbladder pain - being secondary to gallbladder spasm and not inflammation - is often most marked as referred pain to the epigastrium. In the older patient it may be mistaken for cardiac ischaemic pain. Certainly, in the older patient, an ECG would be an essential part of the diagnostic process. The pain of biliary colic is constant in nature and can last anything from a few minutes to several hours. It can radiate round to the back. Pancreatitis is another condition that must be considered in patients presenting with acute epigastric pain - but the pain would be persistent and not resolve within a few hours - as this case describes. Since the diagnosis of biliary colic is the most likely pathological process to have produced this patient\u0027s symptoms, the presence of gallstones should be sought, where \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E has excellent diagnostic accuracy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther diagnoses such as aortic dissection could be considered, but in the absence of hypertension, this is an underlying cause of this otherwise well 42-year-old man. If an ultrasound examination did not show gallstones, the scan would almost certainly look at other structures within the abdominal cavity - including the aorta. If his pain had been cardiac in origin, it is most unlikely that it would have settled so rapidly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In suspected acute biliary pain, ultrasonography should be the initial diagnostic investigation."],"references":["Gurusamy KS, Davidson BR. Gallstones. BMJ 2014; 348:g2669."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74746"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1867"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74746"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T09:13:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T09:13:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1867"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90506"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https